        {
            "texttype":"Online",
            "textpurpose":"Didactics",
            "textentryhtml":"The iconographic and stylistic depiction of luohans, guardians of the Buddhist law, spans a wide spectrum-from grotesque to refined-but the intent of this theme was to convey a sense of profound self-realization. In this painting, vivid, bold brushstrokes define the misshapen head and robes of the luohan, who manipulates a magic pearl that subdues a dragon writhing in the mist. This scene may represent the theme of a luohan \"[Causing] the dragon to descend,\" possibly implying the victory of Buddhist law over cosmic forces. Despite areas of damage and repair at the lower right corner and in the clouds around the dragon's head, the surviving brush lines and subtle ink wash playfully interact with the figures, raising questions about the perceived relationships between substance and appearance, reality and unreality. It has been suggested that the style of the painting may have a connection to regional painting schools in Fujian or Guangdong provinces in southern China.",
            "remarks":null
        }
